            Why the 18 Month Sleep Regression Happens
          </h2>
          <p>
            Around 18 months, your toddler is going through what I call a "developmental perfect storm." Multiple big changes are happening simultaneously, and together they create the conditions for disrupted sleep.
          </p>

          <h3 className="text-xl font-bold text-brand-charcoal mt-8 mb-3">Separation Anxiety Peaks</h3>
          <p>
            According to the American Academy of Pediatrics, separation anxiety often reaches its peak between 10 and 18 months. Your toddler now fully understands that you exist when they can't see you â€” but they haven't yet developed the emotional maturity to feel secure about it. At bedtime, this translates into panic when you leave the room.
          </p>

          <h3 className="text-xl font-bold text-brand-charcoal mt-8 mb-3">The Language Explosion</h3>
          <p>
            Around 18 months, most toddlers experience a burst in language development. They're learning new words daily, their comprehension is skyrocketing, and their brain is literally rewiring itself. This cognitive overdrive doesn't shut off at bedtime â€” it keeps their brain buzzing when they should be winding down.
          </p>

          <h3 className="text-xl font-bold text-brand-charcoal mt-8 mb-3">Testing Independence and Boundaries</h3>
          <p>
            This is the factor that makes the 18 month regression different from every regression that came before it. Your toddler is discovering that they have a will of their own, and bedtime is a prime opportunity to exercise it. They're not just struggling to sleep â€” they're actively choosing to resist it.
          </p>

          <h3 className="text-xl font-bold text-brand-charcoal mt-8 mb-3">Teething Pain</h3>
          <p>
            At around 18 months, the canine teeth and first molars are pushing through. These are larger teeth that can cause significant discomfort, especially at night when there are fewer distractions. If your toddler is drooling excessively, chewing on things, or has swollen gums, teething is likely playing a role.
          </p>

          <h3 className="text-xl font-bold text-brand-charcoal mt-8 mb-3">The Nap Transition</h3>
          <p>
            Many toddlers are in the process of transitioning from two naps to one nap around this age. This schedule shift can temporarily throw off their entire sleep balance, leading to overtiredness at bedtime and increased night wakings.
          </p>

