          </h2>
          <p>
            Many sleep consultants, myself included, consider the 18 month regression one of the toughest. Here's why it's different from the regressions you've already survived:
          </p>
          <p>
            The 4-month regression was about sleep cycle changes. The 8-month regression was about physical milestones like crawling and pulling up. Those were purely developmental â€” your baby wasn't <em>choosing</em> to fight sleep.
          </p>
          <p>
            At 18 months, there's a new element: <strong>wilful resistance</strong>. Your toddler isn't just struggling to sleep because their brain is developing. They're also <em>choosing</em> to push back, test limits, and assert their independence. This combination of developmental disruption and behavioural defiance is what makes it so exhausting for parents.
          </p>
          <p>
