          </p>

          <h3 className="text-xl font-bold text-brand-charcoal mt-8 mb-3">R â€” Reset: Optimise the Sleep Environment</h3>
          <p>
            Small environmental tweaks can make a significant difference. Ensure the room is genuinely dark (not just dim â€” use blackout curtains or blinds). Use consistent white noise to mask household sounds. Check the room temperature is between 18-20Â°C. And if your toddler doesn't already have a comfort object (a "lovey"), now is the time to introduce one â€” it provides reassurance when you're not in the room.
          </p>

          <h3 className="text-xl font-bold text-brand-charcoal mt-8 mb-3">E â€” Emotionally Connect: Build Security Without Dependence</h3>
          <p>
            This is where the 18 month regression requires a different approach from earlier ones. Your toddler needs extra connection and reassurance during the day to feel secure at night. Spend 10-15 minutes of focused, one-on-one time before the bedtime routine begins. Use a specific phrase or ritual to signal safety â€” something like "I'll always come back. I love you. Time for sleep."
          </p>
          <p>
            The goal is to fill their emotional cup <em>before</em> bed, so they're not desperately seeking connection at 2 AM.
          </p>

          <h3 className="text-xl font-bold text-brand-charcoal mt-8 mb-3">A â€” Adapt: Adjust the Schedule to Their Current Needs</h3>
          <p>
            At 18 months, most toddlers need about 11 to 14 hours of total sleep in 24 hours. If they're still on two naps, this may be the time to consolidate to one longer midday nap. Wake windows at this age are typically 4.5 to 5.5 hours. If your toddler is fighting bedtime, their last wake window may need to be slightly longer.
          </p>
          <p>
            Also consider what happens <em>during</em> wake windows. Toddlers who haven't burned enough physical energy during the day will struggle to settle at night. Active play, outdoor time, and physical exploration are essential.
          </p>

          <h3 className="text-xl font-bold text-brand-charcoal mt-8 mb-3">M â€” Master: Stay Consistent and Set Gentle Limits</h3>
          <p>
            Consistency is your most powerful tool during this regression. Keep your bedtime routine the same every night â€” bath, pyjamas, two books, a cuddle, and goodnight. Don't add extra steps to compensate for the regression, as these become new expectations.
          </p>
          <p>
            When your toddler tests the boundaries (and they will), respond with calm, loving firmness. "I know you want another story. We read two stories. It's time for sleep now. I love you." Then follow through. Every time you hold the boundary, you're teaching them that bedtime is safe, predictable, and non-negotiable.
          </p>

          {/* Section 7 */}
