            Handling the 18 Month Nap Regression
          </h2>
          <p>
            Nap resistance is one of the most frustrating parts of this regression. Your toddler may suddenly refuse their afternoon nap, leading to an overtired meltdown by late afternoon and an even harder bedtime.
          </p>
          <p>
            Here's the key principle: <strong>don't drop the nap too early</strong>. Most 18 month olds still need one nap per day, even if they're fighting it. A toddler refusing a nap doesn't always mean they don't need it â€” it often means they're too wired from developmental changes to settle.
          </p>
          <p>
            If they're still on two naps, the regression may be signalling that it's time to transition to one nap. The signs that they're ready include: consistently fighting the second nap, taking longer than 20 minutes to fall asleep for nap 2, or the second nap pushing bedtime later.
          </p>
          <p>
            When making the transition, shift the single nap to around 12:00-12:30 PM and aim for 1.5 to 2.5 hours. You may need to move bedtime earlier temporarily (as early as 6:30 PM) while they adjust.
          </p>

