            5 Mistakes That Make the 18 Month Sleep Regression Worse
          </h2>
          <ol className="space-y-4 my-6">
            <li>
              <strong className="text-brand-charcoal">Creating new sleep props.</strong> Starting to rock, feed, or lie with your toddler to get them to sleep might provide short-term relief, but it creates a new association that they'll need every time they wake â€” which extends the regression from weeks into months.
            </li>
            <li>
              <strong className="text-brand-charcoal">Assuming they're done with naps.</strong> An 18 month old fighting naps doesn't mean they've outgrown them. Dropping naps too early leads to chronic overtiredness, which paradoxically makes night sleep worse.
            </li>
            <li>
              <strong className="text-brand-charcoal">Pushing bedtime later.</strong> Parents often think keeping their toddler up later will make them more tired and sleep better. The opposite is true. Overtired toddlers produce cortisol (the stress hormone), which makes it harder to fall asleep and stay asleep.
            </li>
            <li>
              <strong className="text-brand-charcoal">Being inconsistent with boundaries.</strong> If you hold the line on "no more stories" three nights in a row, then give in on night four, you've taught your toddler that persistence pays off. They'll escalate their efforts, making future bedtimes even harder.
            </li>
            <li>
              <strong className="text-brand-charcoal">Trying multiple methods at once.</strong> Switching between different approaches every few nights doesn't give any single method time to work. Choose one approach and commit to it for at least a week before evaluating.
            </li>
          </ol>

          {/* Section 9 */}
          <h2 id="when-to-worry" className="text-2xl md:text-3xl font-bold text-brand-charcoal mt-12 mb-4">
            When to Call Your Paediatrician
          </h2>
          <p>
            While the 18 month sleep regression is a normal developmental phase, there are times when professional guidance is warranted. Contact your child's doctor if:
          </p>
          <ul className="space-y-2 my-4">
            <li>The sleep disruption lasts longer than 6 weeks with no improvement</li>
            <li>Your toddler seems to be in pain (pulling at ears, fever, or unusual crying)</li>
            <li>They're snoring loudly or appear to have difficulty breathing during sleep</li>
            <li>There's been a significant change in appetite, energy levels, or developmental progress</li>
            <li>You suspect an ear infection, illness, or other medical issue</li>
          </ul>
          <p>
            It's always better to rule out physical causes early, especially since ear infections and teething pain can mimic sleep regression symptoms.
          </p>

